Allocations

Syrup is designed to provide fashion and apparel merchandisers and allocators with initial allocation and replenishment recommendations for their store network. With Syrup, you can streamline your inventory and optimize product distribution so that you can maximize sales and increase revenue.

8b2b2d90-0b26-4667-be03-7d7bebedffc3.text:
Features

Syrup offers a range of features to help you manage your inventory and optimize your product distribution. Some of these features include:

- **Initial** **Allocation Recommendations:** Syrup provides initial allocation recommendations based on your store network and sales data. These recommendations can help you determine how much inventory to send to each store and when to send it.
- **Replenishment Recommendations:** Syrup provides replenishment recommendations based on sales data and inventory levels. These recommendations can help you determine when to restock inventory and how much inventory to restock.

1. How does your application work?

dc5439c3-d3ea-42a2-8fc1-ab8e2bdb46c5.text:
Initial Allocations

The Initial Allocations feature in Syrup is a game-changer for fashion brands looking to allocate new inventory to their store network. This feature allows brands to easily and efficiently allocate their new inventory to the right stores, ensuring that the right products are available to the right customers at the right time.

With Initial Allocations, brands can save time and money by automating the allocation process. This feature takes into account past sales data, current inventory levels, and other relevant factors to make informed allocation decisions. Brands can also set specific allocation rules based on factors such as store location, customer demographics, and sales history.

The Initial Allocations feature is designed to be user-friendly and intuitive. Brands can easily set up and manage their allocation rules, and the system will automatically generate allocation recommendations based on those rules. Brands can then review and approve these recommendations before they are executed.

Overall, the Initial Allocations feature in Syrup is a powerful tool for fashion brands looking to optimize their inventory allocation process. By automating allocation decisions and providing data-driven recommendations, this feature helps brands save time, reduce costs, and improve their overall performance.

19057f9e-ab6c-4fe3-998f-0b554b5ca4e9.text:
Reorders

Reorders is a powerful module in Syrup that enables fashion brands to optimize their inventory management. With Reorders, brands can ensure that they reorder the right amount of product at the right time, which can help to increase full-price sell-through and improve working capital.

Reorders is specifically designed to help fashion brands streamline their inventory management processes. By providing real-time data on inventory levels, sales trends, and customer demand, Reorders helps brands make informed decisions about when and how much inventory to reorder. This can help to reduce overstocking and ensure that popular items are always in stock.

Another key benefit of Reorders is that it can help brands to increase their full-price sell-through. By ensuring that popular items are always in stock, brands can reduce the need for markdowns and promotions, which can erode margins and damage brand equity. This can help to improve profitability and customer loyalty over the long term.

Finally, Reorders can also help brands to improve their working capital. By reducing the amount of excess inventory on hand, brands can free up cash that can be used to invest in other areas of the business. This can help to fuel growth and support strategic initiatives.

Overall, Reorders is an essential tool for any fashion brand looking to optimize their inventory management processes and improve their bottom line. With its real-time data, powerful analytics, and intuitive interface, Reorders is a must-have module for any brand looking to stay ahead of the competition.

fc3b3156-4137-4065-b3d9-04365e724055.text:
Replenishments

Replenishments are an important feature in Syrup that is designed specifically for fashion buyers and merchandisers. Replenishments refer to the process of restocking inventory that is running low or has been completely sold out.

As a fashion buyer or merchandiser, you understand the importance of keeping your inventory levels at the optimal level to meet customer demand. Our replenishment feature helps you accomplish this by providing you with real-time data on which products are running low on stock and need to be restocked.

Syrup automatically generates replenishment recommendations so stockouts are prevented and full-price sellthrough is accomplished. 

By using our replenishment feature, you can avoid stockouts and ensure that your customers always have access to the products they want. This not only improves customer satisfaction but also helps you increase your sales and revenue.

In conclusion, our replenishment feature is an essential tool for fashion buyers and merchandisers who want to stay on top of their inventory levels and meet customer demand. If you have any questions or need assistance in using this feature, please do not hesitate to contact our customer support team.

Overview

Syrup is an intelligent platform that helps organizations achieve inventory excellence. It offers modules for store-to-store transfers, DC-to-store transfers, initial allocations, reorders, new store openings, compliance, and configurations. The platform helps organizations move inventory efficiently to increase revenue and improve working capital. The modules are designed to address specific inventory management needs, and configurations allow companies to set business rules that reflect their specific ways of doing business.

e5f6dc3f-a942-4064-9ebc-b35056262aee.text:
Store to Store Transfers

Put simply, this page helps organizations move inventory from one location to another with the goal of increasing revenue and improving working capital. 

Imagine a scenario where you have a t-shirt selling really well at a specific location. As a retailer you have a few different options available to you:

1. Just run out of inventory. 
    1. Not ideal, this would allow you to miss out on real sales. 
2. Purchase more from your vendor
    1. Most of the time, not ideal. There is often significant lead time to get new inventory in stock. If the volume is high enough, perhaps this SHOULD be done, but that also means your initial projections were quite a ways off, so its addressing a symptom and perhaps not the root cause of the real issue. 
3. Utilize inventory from another location where there is extra inventory.
    1. Quite often ideal, the organization gets to utilize inventory from a location where they likely wouldn't have sold out anyways. Instead of wasted inventory stores can capture that revenue. There is a small cost associated with routing inventory, but if done correctly that can be minimized. 
4. Move inventory from the Distribution Center to the Store
    1. 👇

602ba7bf-1382-46ba-bea1-81eb8780e77f.text:
DC to Store transfers

Quite often retailers store excess inventory in their Distribution Centers with the goal of having a central hub they can work from to fulfill inventory needs on a store by store basis. At the start of a season there is an initial allocation that happens on a store by store basis. These projections are an imperfect prediction and are a combination of art and science. 

*The DC to Store transfers help organizations re-balance their inventory and send inventory from the DC to the store where there is likely to be a supply shortage or stockout.*

6bb961c1-9c57-4d1a-8679-0f63fd5a5723.text:
Initial Allocations

Initial Allocations is like DC to store transfers, but they are happening at the start of the season (ie when there is no existing inventory in the store for those articles) We have no sales history about these items.

13e49a33-1b8d-4955-9695-e1aad2b86a72.text:
Reorders

Reorders helps organizations know what to purchase from their supplier/vendor.

7fa3ddd3-6df8-4e1e-8895-b84df0a62e3a.text:
New Store Openings

As retailers expand and grow they may decide to open new stores to try to capture revenue in a different region. They may open up new stores at a number of times throughout the year. When opening up new stores organizations have to ask the questions, what inventory should I have at this location. 

The new store openings page helps organizations transfer inventory to new stores so that the store can…well…open…and they can send excess inventory from locations where supply is higher than the demand with the help of New Store Opening transfers. 

This allows organizations to effectively open stores faster, and more efficiently by taking advantage of excess inventory at other stores.
